Session `03_image_based_surface_estimation` implements
`estimate_surface_and_l2_image_based()` in
`code/dev_code/03_image_based_surface.py`.  Two-stage:

1. **Global baseline** from the top 1–2 z-planes pooled across the
   whole image (median + 1.4826·MAD; skip planes ≥ 95 % zero; drop
   exact-zero padding voxels).  HCR pure-padding top → fallback
   `σ = 0.02 · percentile(vol, 99)`.  Threshold =
   `max(bg + 6σ, bg + 0.02·dyn_hint)`.
2. **Per-tile onset** (80 µm HCR / 60 µm CZ) — 1-D median-along-z
   profile, Gaussian-smooth, first-sustained-above-thr run of
   ≥ `min_thick_surface_um` µm within the top 30 % of z.  Fit quadratic
   `z = a·x + b·y + c + p·x² + q·x·y + r·y²` via IRLS-Huber.

Driver + figures in `03_image_based_surface_run.py` /
`03_image_based_surface_figs.py`; results + log in
`sessions/03_image_based_surface_estimation/`.

**Why:** The previous per-column-in-band port of N22 was too complex
and still flat; user asked for a simpler global-stats approach.
L2 was explicitly dropped (CZ L2 ambiguous in side views).  No ROI
clamp — explicitly image-only.

**How to apply:** Onset_depth 2.5 µm on every HCR subject; CZ resid
MAD < 3.3 µm on every subject.  Walkthroughs confirm the red surface
hugs the tissue top.  above_frac still 1.4–10 % on HCR (no ROI clamp)
— treat this session as a complementary image-driven cross-check for
pia, not a replacement for N22.

**Known outliers (2026-04-17):** HCR resid_mad highest on 767022/755252
(74 / 66 µm — 80-µm tiles are noisy); CZ above_frac highest on 782149
(8.3 % — unusually bright upper-layer GFP+ cells).  Open: quantile
loss at q≈0.80 for HCR might close above_frac gap without hurting CZ.
